article.headline: Pondexter sets rookie mark in Mercury's victory
article.linkText: Pondexter sets rookie mark in Mercury's victory
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Diana Taurasi was one of the greatest
players in NCAA history and is now one of the biggest stars of the
WNBA.

On Thursday night, she wasn't the best player on her own team.

Cappie Pondexter scored a league rookie-record 35 points to lead
Taurasi and the Phoenix Mercury to a 91-76 win over the Detroit
Shock.

"I'd like to pretend that I'm shocked and surprised, but I'm
really not," Taurasi said. "It has been amazing to see what
Cappie can do on the floor."

Pondexter's scoring total was the highest by a rookie in the
WNBA's 10 seasons, breaking the record of 32 set earlier this
season by Minnesota's Seimone Augustus.

"I don't think she's really a rookie," Taurasi said,
pretending not to notice that Pondexter was sitting next to her.
"I think she was held back in kindergarten and she's really 25."

Pondexter was 12-of-19 from the floor and 7-for-7 from the
free-throw line.

"I had to check the box to see if she missed a shot," Phoenix
coach Paul Westhead said. "She's lethal out there."

The loss ended Detroit's 13-game home winning streak, dating
back to July 17, 2005.

"We were unprepared to play basketball tonight," Shock coach
Bill Laimbeer said. "That's the bottom line. They thought they
were so good that they'd just go out there and win. Hopefully, they
found out differently."

The Shock have lost two of three after a six-game winning
streak, while the Mercury snapped a two-game losing skid.

"I just knew we needed to win," Pondexter said. "We weren't
focused on how well they were playing, we just want to win as many
road games as possible."

Kelly Miller added 14 points for Phoenix, while Taurasi had 13
after playing most of the night in foul trouble. Taurasi entered
the game as the league's leading scorer, but Pondexter moved past
her and Augustus to take over the lead.

"She's a great player," Detroit's Cheryl Ford said. "It is as
simple as that."

Deanna Nolan led the Shock with 15 points, but All-Stars Ruth
Riley, Swin Cash and Ford combined for seven points on 3-for-14
shooting. Detroit finished with 23 turnovers, matching a season
high.

Nolan scored the first basket of the game, but Phoenix scored
the next four points and never trailed again. The Mercury led by as
many as 27 down the stretch.
